s a novelist, Federman (1928–2009) is also the author of numerous books of poetry, essays, translations, and criticism. After emigrating to the United States in 1942 and receiving a Ph.D. in comparative literature at UCLA in 1957, he held professorships in the University at Buffalo's departments of French and English from 1964 to 1999. Together with Steve Katz and Ronald Sukenick, he was one of the original founders of the Fiction Collective, a nonprofit publishing house dedicated to avant garde, experimental prose. Far too many accounts treat Federman as merely a member of a small group of writers who pioneered "metafictional" or "postmodern" American literature. Federman's Fiction will introduce (or, for some, reintroduce) to the broader scholarly community a creative and daring thinker whose work is significant not just to considerations of the development of innovative fiction, but to a number of other distinct disciplines and emerging critical discourses.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aHistory : Holocaust Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Literature. 4aPhilosophy : Postmodernism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aBaetens, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornis-Pope, Marcel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Leo, Jeffrey R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Leo, Jeffrey R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFederman, Raymond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeuer, Menachem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerdes, Ec